		Comment <a href="#c_1713649601">20</a> by Dan G. Switzer, II
		posted on 1/26/2006 at 9:30 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>Raymond,</p><p>I disagree about the SQL Server issue. I think *some* issues should be published. While this certainly shouldn't be a SQL cookbook by any means, I do think there are certain issues that should be addressed. However, instead of having different questions/answers for each database, I think the attempt should be made to give an answer for the main dbs (SQL Server/Oracle) and then advice on how to approach the problem.</p><p>For example, the one question that constantly shows up on CF-Talk, is the correct way to get the primary key of the record just inserted.</p><p>I think this issue is important enough that it should be covered. There's only one really reliable way to handle this in SQL Server, and it's to use the SCOPE_IDENTITY() function:</p><p>[CFQUERY]<br>insert into [Table] (<br>  column1, <br>  column2<br>) values (<br>  #value1#,<br>  #value2#<br>)</p><p>select SCOPE_IDENTITY() as newId<br>[/CFQUERY]</p><p>In these cases there a very proven techniques that should be used over other solutions. These are the type of SQL questions I think should be addressed. I'd be very selective of the type of SQL questions that do get answered, but I'd at least address some of the very common core issues a developer will face.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
		
